```typescript
const outcomes = await Promise.all(
  deliveryIds.map(async (id) => {
    try { await processDelivery(id); return { ok: true, id }; }
    catch (err) { return { ok: false, id, error: err.message }; }
  })
);
results.processed = outcomes.filter(o => o.ok).length;
results.failed = outcomes.filter(o => !o.ok).length;
results.errors = outcomes.filter(o => !o.ok).map(o => ({ id: o.id, error: o.error! }));
```
Option B: use `Promise.allSettled` for the same pattern with clearer semantics.","time_to_fix":"15 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Batch result counts must equal input count; error list must be complete"},{"title":"Unbounded concurrency — 500 parallel network/IO calls with no concurrency limit","risk":"Firing 500 `processDelivery` calls simultaneously can exhaust connection pools, file descriptors, or downstream rate limits, causing mass timeouts or cascading failures. This also amplifies the race condition above.","severity":"High","location":"processBatchDeliveries — `Promise.all(deliveryIds.map(...))`","reproduction":"Call with 500 IDs against a service with a connection pool of 50. Observe connection exhaustion errors, timeouts, or HTTP 429s.","fix":"Use a concurrency limiter (e.g. `p-limit`, `Promise` chunking, or a semaphore):
```typescript
import pLimit from 'p-limit';
const limit = pLimit(20); // tune to downstream capacity
await Promise.all(deliveryIds.map(id => limit(() => processDelivery(id))));
```","time_to_fix":"15 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Batch processing must complete reliably without overwhelming downstream services"},{"title":"`err.message` access on untyped catch — runtime TypeError if error is not an Error","risk":"If `processDelivery` throws a string, number, or undefined (common with third-party libs or rejected promises), accessing `.message` on a non-Error value throws a TypeError, converting a handled failure into an unhandled crash that breaks the entire batch.","severity":"High","location":"processBatchDeliveries — `catch (err)` block, `err.message`","reproduction":"Have `processDelivery` do `throw 'connection refused'` (a string). The catch block accesses `.message` on a string primitive — returns `undefined` silently (not a crash in this case, but loses error info). Worse: `throw undefined` → `err.message` throws TypeError.","fix":"```typescript
